michigan_body = "{\"ops\":[{\"attributes\":{\"link\":\"http://www.michigan.org/travel/\",\"bold\":true,\"color\":\"rgb(37, 37, 37)\"},\"insert\":\"Michigan\"},{\"insert\":\" (pronounced \\\"MISH-i-g'n\\\") is an \"},{\"attributes\":{\"link\":\"https://en.wikivoyage.org/wiki/United_States_of_America\",\"color\":\"rgb(11, 0, 128)\"},\"insert\":\"American\"},{\"insert\":\" state in the upper \"},{\"attributes\":{\"link\":\"https://en.wikivoyage.org/wiki/Midwest_(United_States_of_America)\",\"color\":\"rgb(11, 0, 128)\"},\"insert\":\"Midwest\"},{\"insert\":\" and the heart of the Great Lakes region. It has many attractions, famous landmarks, and scenic state and national parks and forests. In addition to the great ones, it has about 12,000 inland lakes, 38 deep-water ports, more miles of coastline than any state but Alaska, and more lighthouses than any other U.S. state. Its agriculture features tourist-friendly fare such as cherries, blueberries, peaches, apples, and wine. And its cities include a major metropolis, university towns, and countless rustic villages.\\n\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"image\":\"http://mynorth.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/Shalda-Creek-Michigan.jpg\"},\"insert\":1},{\"insert\":\"\\n\"}]}"
